The central technical challenge in building such a surrogate is the \textbf{exposure bias problem} inherent in autoregressive sequence generation (Hall et al., 2025). During training, a sequence-to-sequence model receives ground-truth process variable values as inputs to the decoder at each timestep. During deployment, however, the model must feed its own previous predictions back as inputs over a 180-second rollout horizon. Small prediction errors at early steps compound through the recurrent state across the remaining steps, causing the generated trajectory to drift away from the true physical dynamics — a phenomenon that is especially severe for slow-dynamics channels such as tank level and cooling temperature, whose physical states evolve on timescales of minutes. Addressing this challenge through scheduled sampling and systematic hyperparameter optimisation is one of the principal technical contributions of this work.

\subsection{Objectives}

The work reported in this document pursues the following seven objectives, each stated with a specific and verifiable success criterion.

\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{Objective 1 — Physics-informed modular architecture.}
Design and implement a closed-loop surrogate architecture for the HAI ICS
boiler subsystem that decomposes the industrial process into independently
trainable per-loop controllers (PC, LC, FC, TC, CC) and a shared plant
encoder-decoder model. The architecture must function as both a
\textbf{simulator} (learning the causal mapping from control variables to
process variables) and a \textbf{conditional generator} (producing
scenario-specific sensor trajectories). It must mirror the physical
independence of the real PID control loops and support modular deployment
and maintenance in real industrial environments.

\item \textbf{Objective 2 — Dual-architecture training and evaluation.}
Train and evaluate two recurrent neural network architectures — a Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) primary model and a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) baseline model (GeeksforGeeks, 2026; Hall et al., 2025) — on the HAI 23.05 dataset under all four attack scenarios. The controlled architectural comparison, using identical data, pipeline, and feature sets, isolates the effect of recurrent cell type on closed-loop simulation fidelity.

\item \textbf{Objective 3 — Exposure bias mitigation via scheduled sampling.}
Quantify the impact of scheduled sampling on closed-loop autoregressive prediction stability by systematically evaluating SS\_MAX $\in \{0.0, 0.5\}$ and extended curriculum ramp schedules for both architectures, and report the resulting improvement in mean NRMSE relative to the pure teacher-forcing baseline.

\item \textbf{Objective 4 — Gate-threshold compliance.}
Achieve a closed-loop Normalised Root Mean Square Error (NRMSE) below 10\% on all five process variable channels for both the primary and baseline models after tuning. This threshold constitutes the operational deployment criterion, ensuring that the surrogate's simulation fidelity is sufficient for reliable anomaly detection without excessive false-positive rates.

\item \textbf{Objective 5 — Long-horizon prediction stability assessment.}
Characterise the long-horizon autoregressive stability of the GRU primary model by evaluating multi-horizon rollouts extending to 1.5 hours (5,400 consecutive prediction timesteps), determining whether the model maintains per-channel NRMSE below the deployment gate threshold across all evaluated horizon lengths beyond the training rollout window.

\item \textbf{Objective 6 — Evidence-based architecture comparison for deployment.}
Compare the deployment trade-offs between the GRU primary model and the LSTM baseline across prediction accuracy, computational efficiency, parameter count, training time, pre-tuning stability, and robustness across attack scenario types, to produce evidence-based recommendations for architecture selection in resource-constrained real-time ICS monitoring deployments.

\item \textbf{Objective 7 — Scalable real-time deployment architecture.}
Design a modular deployment architecture for the GRU digital twin simulator and generator that supports edge deployment across multiple microgrid facilities, 1 Hz real-time inference, horizontal scaling through parallel Plant and Controller execution, and continuous anomaly detection with automated alerting and audit logging.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Relevance to Real-World Applications and Academic Research}

\subsubsection{Industrial and Operational Relevance}

The threat to industrial control systems is neither theoretical nor rare. The Stuxnet worm demonstrated in 2010 that ICS software can be targeted with surgical precision to cause physical damage while evading conventional monitoring. The 2015 and 2016 attacks on Ukrainian power distribution infrastructure demonstrated that coordinated manipulation of ICS actuators can disable power delivery to hundreds of thousands of people within minutes. In water treatment, attacks on supervisory control systems have the potential to alter chemical dosing processes with direct consequences for public health. These incidents share a common characteristic: the attack was designed to \emph{appear normal} to threshold-based alarms while gradually or suddenly driving the physical process toward a dangerous state.

The digital twin framework developed in this work addresses this threat class directly. Because the surrogate models the \emph{expected dynamic behaviour} of the entire process — including the physical coupling between pressure, level, flow, and temperature that arises from shared heat exchange and fluid transport — it can detect coordinated multi-loop attacks through the accumulated residual across channels, even when no single sensor reading is individually anomalous (Homaei et al., 2026). The large P1\_LIT01 residual observed under the AP With Combination attack scenario in this work demonstrates this property concretely: the surrogate generates its strongest anomaly signal for the most dangerous attack type, which is precisely the operationally desired behaviour for a security monitoring system.

The architecture's design for edge deployment at individual microgrid facilities — rather than centralised cloud processing — directly addresses the latency and communication reliability requirements of real-time industrial monitoring. A cloud-dependent monitoring system introduces communication delay between the physical event and the detection response, and creates a single point of failure if the communication link is disrupted or attacked. The modular separation of Plant and Controller models further enables deployment across facilities with varying control loop configurations without requiring full retraining of the entire system.

\subsubsection{Academic and Research Relevance}

This work makes four contributions of broader relevance to the fields of machine learning for time series, industrial AI, and cyber-physical system security.

\textbf{Scheduled sampling for ICS closed-loop surrogate models.}
The systematic investigation of scheduled sampling as a curriculum learning intervention for the exposure bias problem in closed-loop recurrent surrogates contributes to the growing literature on autoregressive training for industrial time-series forecasting (Hall et al., 2025). The 82\% improvement in mean NRMSE for the GRU and 54\% for the LSTM through scheduled sampling and extended curriculum ramps provides quantitative evidence — on a real ICS security dataset with 52 documented attack scenarios — that this technique is highly effective for multi-step process simulation, where the long-range physical coupling between variables amplifies the consequences of exposure bias far beyond what is typically observed in standard time-series benchmarks.

\textbf{Controlled architectural comparison of GRU and LSTM for industrial digital twins.}
The controlled architectural comparison between GRU and LSTM — using identical data, pipeline, feature sets, and evaluation metrics — provides a rigorous empirical basis for the choice of recurrent cell type in ICS surrogate modelling applications. The finding that the GRU's simpler single-state architecture, despite achieving a superior validation loss (0.00055 vs. 0.00063), accumulates more autoregressive error on slow-dynamics channels than the LSTM under identical tuning conditions is a nuanced result that advances the understanding of when the LSTM's explicit cell state provides a measurable practical advantage in closed-loop rollout scenarios. This finding has direct implications for the design of future ICS digital twin systems where the trade-off between model efficiency and long-range memory fidelity must be carefully evaluated.

\textbf{Long-horizon autoregressive stability for extended ICS monitoring.}
The evaluation of multi-horizon rollouts extending to 1.5 hours (5,400 timesteps) for the GRU primary model, with all five channels passing the deployment gate threshold across all evaluated horizon lengths, demonstrates that physics-informed recurrent surrogates can maintain stable prediction stability far beyond the training rollout window. This result is directly relevant to the design of proactive anomaly detection systems that must predict the trajectory of a physical process over extended future windows to identify attacks that gradually and stealthily drive the system toward a dangerous state, rather than causing an immediate detectable spike (Homaei et al., 2026).

\textbf{Physics-informed feature decomposition for cyber-physical security.}
The per-loop controller decomposition adopted in this architecture — which restricts each controller model to the two signals its physical counterpart actually observes — represents a principled approach to domain-knowledge-guided feature engineering that simultaneously improves model interpretability, prevents spurious cross-channel correlation learning, and enables independent per-loop deployment. This connects to the broader research agenda on physics-informed machine learning for cyber-physical systems, where structural domain knowledge is used to constrain the learning problem rather than relying on unconstrained end-to-end optimisation (HAI-Dataset-v4.0; Homaei et al., 2026).

\textbf{Dual-role digital twin as simulator and generator.}
This work demonstrates that a single GRU architecture can simultaneously
serve as a physics-informed simulator (mapping CVs to PVs) and a
conditional generator (producing attack-specific trajectories). The
evaluation framework separately assesses simulation accuracy (NRMSE,
per-loop performance, error accumulation) and generation quality
(scenario overlay plots, attack detection via residuals). This dual-role
design enables the model to both simulate expected normal behaviour and
generate attack-conditioned trajectories for detection, unifying two
traditionally separate functions in a single architecture.

\section{Literature Review and Background}

Industrial Control Systems (ICS) form the operational backbone of critical infrastructure such as water treatment facilities, manufacturing plants, energy networks, and automated production environments. As these systems become increasingly integrated with digital communication networks, they are exposed to greater cybersecurity risks and operational disruptions. Unlike traditional information systems, failures or attacks within ICS environments may directly impact physical processes, causing production losses, equipment damage, safety hazards, and service interruption. Consequently, there has been growing research interest in intelligent anomaly detection techniques capable of identifying abnormal behaviour in cyber-physical systems.

Conventional ICS monitoring approaches relied on fixed thresholds, rule-based alarms, and signature-based intrusion detection mechanisms. While these methods are simple to implement, they often struggle to detect sophisticated attacks or subtle process deviations where individual sensor values appear normal but hidden temporal relationships indicate abnormal behaviour. To overcome these limitations, recent studies have increasingly adopted machine learning methods that learn operational patterns directly from historical process data.

Unsupervised learning has been widely explored for industrial anomaly detection because labelled attack datasets are often limited. Inoue et al. (2017) developed an anomaly detection framework for a water treatment system using unsupervised machine learning, demonstrating that data-driven approaches can identify abnormal operational states without requiring labelled attack samples. More recently, Agure and Nggada (2025) proposed a real-time anomaly detection system for industrial cyber-physical systems using unsupervised models such as autoencoders and clustering algorithms, highlighting the importance of lightweight and adaptive monitoring solutions for modern Industry 4.0 environments.

Deep learning methods have also shown strong capability in modelling sequential industrial data. Feng et al. (2017) introduced a multi-level anomaly detection framework for industrial control systems that combines packet signatures with Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks. Their results showed that recurrent neural architectures are effective for learning temporal dependencies in industrial traffic and process signals. These findings are directly relevant to this project, where recurrent models are evaluated for predictive anomaly detection through multistep forecasting.

Recent research has further explored scalable and transferable learning architectures. Ehrhardt et al. (2024) proposed modular neural networks for anomaly detection in cyber-physical systems, demonstrating that decomposing complex systems into smaller specialised models can improve interpretability, maintainability, and scalability. Similarly, Wang et al. (2021) applied transfer learning for ICS anomaly detection, showing that knowledge learned from one environment can improve detection performance in another system. These approaches closely align with the methodology of this project, where the industrial plant is represented through modular subsystems and lightweight predictive models.

Despite significant progress, several research gaps remain. Many previous studies focus primarily on classification-based anomaly detection rather than predictive closed-loop digital twin modelling. Other works evaluate only one architecture or limited attack scenarios, making direct comparison difficult under consistent experimental conditions. In addition, fewer studies investigate the balance between forecasting accuracy, long-horizon stability, and real-time deployment efficiency.

This project addresses these gaps by developing a modular closed-loop  digital twin  for industrial process monitoring and comparing recurrent neural architectures under identical training and evaluation settings. Through consistent preprocessing, feature selection, and performance metrics, the study enables fair model comparison while extending current knowledge in multistep forecasting, cyber-attack robustness, and scalable real-time anomaly detection for industrial environments.

\section{Methodology}

\subsection{Obtain Data}

\subsubsection{Data Sourcing}

This work integrates three complementary data sources. The HAI (HIL-based Augmented ICS) Security Dataset, version 23.05 (HAI-Dataset-v4.0), constitutes the primary empirical data source. The testbed faithfully replicates three interconnected real-world industrial processes --- a boiler, a turbine, and a water treatment unit --- coupled to a HIL simulation of a steam/hydro turbine and power grid model, as illustrated in the process flow diagram of the testbed (Figure 1). The physical architecture comprises tanks (TK01--TK04), heat exchangers, pumps, and valves. Collected at 1 Hz, the dataset captures the complete operational state across four signal categories: process variables (PVs) including pressure (P1\_PIT01), water level (P1\_LIT01), flow rate (P1\_FT03Z), and dual temperature readings (P1\_TIT01, P1\_TIT03); control variables (CVs) encoding actuator commands such as valve positions and pump setpoints; setpoints (SPs) representing desired reference values; and auxiliary plant signals providing operational context. Each observation carries a binary attack flag indicating whether an attack is active. The categorical scenario labels used for model conditioning were derived by extracting the defining features of each attack type from the HAI 23.05 technical documentation (HAI-Dataset-v4.0) and mapping them to a four-class scheme based on attack mechanism and process condition, as summarised in Table~\ref{tab:attack_taxonomy}.

