\subsubsection{Synthetic Data Generation}
\label{sec:synth_quality}

This section evaluates the quality of the synthetic data produced by the digital twin’s conditional generation capability. The key question is whether the generated trajectories are statistically close to real sensor recordings — a prerequisite for any downstream use of synthetic data in security analysis.

To verify this, the model was conditioned on each attack scenario label (AP\_no, AP\_with, AE\_no) and used to generate 3{,}292 synthetic 180-second windows — matching the size of the Normal class in the test set. The generated PV trajectories were then compared against the real recorded trajectories for each scenario.

Figure~\ref{fig:synth_quality} shows the mean $\pm$ standard deviation of the five process variables over time for each attack scenario, comparing real recordings (black) against synthetic generation (coloured dashed). Across all three attack scenarios and all five PVs, the synthetic mean closely tracks the real mean throughout the prediction horizon. The spread (standard deviation bands) of synthetic trajectories overlaps substantially with that of real trajectories, confirming that the model reproduces not only the central tendency but also the natural variability of real attack dynamics.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=1.0\textwidth]{s3_experement/s3c_data_quality.png}
\caption{Real vs.\ synthetic PV trajectories per attack scenario (mean $\pm$ std). Each row is one attack scenario; each column is one process variable. Black: real recordings. Dashed coloured: model-generated synthetic data.}
\label{fig:synth_quality}
\end{figure}

The alignment is strongest for AP\_no and AE\_no, where the generated mean follows the real mean with minimal offset across all PVs. For AP\_with — the most disruptive attack involving simultaneous multi-loop manipulation and combustion disturbance — the synthetic mean captures the direction and magnitude of the deviation, though with slightly reduced amplitude. This is expected: AP\_with constitutes only 20 training windows, so the model has seen fewer examples of this regime.

\paragraph{Key Insight}

These results confirm that the GRU digital twin successfully operates as a conditional data generator. By conditioning on a scenario embedding, it can synthesise physically plausible, scenario-specific sensor trajectories whose statistical properties match real recordings. This enables the model to artificially balance the highly imbalanced HAI dataset, a property that has direct downstream consequences for attack classification, as evaluated in Section~\ref{sec:attack_classification}.


