\paragraph{Key Insight}
The results reveal that detection performance is strongly dependent on the magnitude and observability of the attack. High-impact attacks such as \textit{AP\_with} generate large deviations from learned system dynamics and are therefore easily detectable. In contrast, low-impact or stealthy attacks (\textit{AP\_no}, \textit{AE\_no}) remain close to the normal operating regime and are difficult to distinguish using residual-based methods.

This highlights an important limitation of the approach: the detector functions as a binary alarm with uneven sensitivity across attack types. While it is effective for identifying strong deviations, it fails to reliably detect subtle manipulations that do not significantly affect observable process variables.

This limitation motivates the need for complementary methods, such as attack classification or multi-modal detection, which can leverage additional signals beyond PV residuals to improve coverage across diverse attack scenarios.

