\section{Discussion and Conclusions}

This project evaluated the use of recurrent neural network digital twins for industrial control system (ICS) monitoring and cyber-attack detection using the HAI 23.05 dataset. Two architectures were compared: a GRU-based primary model and an LSTM-based baseline model. Both models were implemented as closed-loop surrogate systems capable of predicting the future behaviour of five key process variables under both normal and attack scenarios. After optimisation, both architectures achieved less than 10\% NRMSE across all monitored channels, confirming their suitability for deployment in real-time industrial environments.

A major finding of this work was the importance of scheduled sampling in reducing exposure bias during autoregressive forecasting. Both models showed substantial improvement after tuning, with the GRU achieving the best final mean NRMSE of 0.0105 while using fewer parameters and lower computational cost than the LSTM. This makes the GRU more suitable for edge deployment, where efficiency and low latency are critical. The LSTM, however, remained highly competitive and performed strongly on slower levels and thermal variables, benefiting from its dedicated memory cell.

Scenario analysis showed that both models performed best under Actuator Emulation attacks and worst under combined multi-loop actuator attacks, indicating that attack complexity has a greater effect on performance than architecture choice. The tuned GRU also demonstrated strong long-horizon stability, maintaining accurate predictions for up to 1.5 hours, which highlights its value for extended monitoring and early anomaly detection.

Overall, the results demonstrate that physics-informed recurrent digital twins are a practical solution for ICS cybersecurity. They provide continuous prediction-based monitoring capable of detecting stealthy attacks that may bypass traditional alarm systems. Future work may focus on transformer models, graph neural networks, online learning, and deployment on live industrial control platforms.

